                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17720715-25-victim240 t17720715-25-viclabel131"></join> for my own horses, which I let out; I lost a saddle out of my stable, on the 4th of July, which was brought back again about eight o'clock in the morning.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17720715-25-person242">
                  Elisha
                   Wathman
               <interp inst="t17720715-25-person242" type="surname" value="Wathman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17720715-25-person242" type="given" value="Elisha"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17720715-25-person242" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner coming out of Mr. Earl's stable with a saddle in a bag upon his back, at eight o'clock in the morning; I suspected him; I went to Mr. Earl's son, and asked him if he knew the prisoner; he said no; we pursued him, and took him in about three minutes, with the saddle on him.</p>
               <p>Thomas Earl confirmed this evidence.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence</p>
               <p>As I was going through the yard, I met an hostler; he gave me the saddle to carry for him to the Green Man and Still. I served the King twenty-nine years.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177207150020"></xptr>He called a witness, who said he had been formerly transported.</p>
